explanation:
For determining whether any part of OS_DeleteAllObjects is unreachable you must know which called symbols can affect control flow or the loop termination condition:

- OS_ForEachObjectOfType: determines whether ObjectCount (passed by pointer) can be changed and whether this call can not return (e.g. longjmp/abort). Required to know if the per-type cleanup can make ObjectCount zero or otherwise alter loop progress.
- OS_ForEachObject: same reasons as above for the all-type sweep; it directly participates in ObjectCount updates and control-flow outcomes for the loop-break test.
- OS_CleanUpObject: this is the callback passed into the iterator functions. Its behaviour (incrementing/decrementing refcounts, aborting, non-returning, infinite loop) can make iterations succeed/fail or make subsequent code unreachable.
- OS_TaskDelay: called when iteration did not finish; must know whether it returns normally or can block forever/terminate the task (affects reachability of subsequent loop iterations and final break).
- OS_TaskDelay_Impl: the underlying implementation of OS_TaskDelay; include to determine non-returning or terminating behaviour not apparent at the wrapper level.
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMECB, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TASK: the constants passed to OS_ForEachObjectOfType may change which objects are visited; their values themselves are not control-flow altering, but understanding which object classes are affected helps decide whether ObjectCount can reach zero (i.e., whether these calls will make progress).
- OS_OBJECT_CREATOR_ANY: same rationale as above for the creator filter used in the iterators; affects which objects are processed and thus whether ObjectCount can become zero.
- uint32 (typedef): the type of ObjectCount and TryCount — need to ensure arithmetic/overflow behaviour (e.g., if not a regular unsigned 32-bit type) does not make TryCount > 4 check unreachable.
- true (boolean macro or <stdbool.h>): the literal controlling while(true) — include to confirm it expands to an infinite-loop condition and that loop-exit relies on the internal break rather than any alternative language construct.

With these symbols you can reason about (a) whether ObjectCount can become zero, (b) whether TryCount will ever exceed 4, and (c) whether any called function may never return or otherwise make subsequent code unreachable. These are the items required to decide if any part of OS_DeleteAllObjects is unreachable under realistic implementations.
